   <h1>[VB]  6 volt  to 12 volt conversion, is it that easy?</h1>
   <b>jbakerccymca_at_springmail_dot_com</b><br/>
   <i>2002-03-07 14:45:24+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>Thanks Thom.  So, let me see if if I understand the article.  My 12 Volt engine is turnkey complete, so it already has a 12 volt generator (or is it alternator?), coil, and choke, no problem there.  So according to the info, I should be able to put the 6 volt flywheel and clutch onto the 12 volt engine, then simply put the engine into the 1966 bus and use existing 6 volt starter and bell housing configuration and operate the bus off of a 12 volt power source?  That seems WAY too easy, am I missing something?  What about voltage regulator, that would have to be change to a 12 Volt, right? Obviously all bulbs, relays, etc would need to be switched over, but there has got to be something I'm not thinking of, otherwise it's too simple!
Thanks, John Baker


On Wed, 6 Mar 2002 19:50:26 -0800 (PST) Thom Fitzpatrick <thom_at_calweb_dot_com> wrote:

Go to: http://www.vintagebus_dot_com/howto

John Baker wrote:
> OK, I have a good 12 Volt 1600 Dp engine which I want to put into a 6 volt 66 Kombi. Can I really just take the 6 volt flywheel and put it on the 12 volt engine?  What else would need to be changed out?  Voltage Regulator, Bulbs, Wiper motor?
> 
> 
> 
> Peace, John Baker
> 1971 Westy
> 1966 Kombi
> http://www.geocities_dot_com/jbakerccymca
> "...so we got in the red VW microbus with the shovels and rakes and implements of destruction and
> headed on to the police officer's station..."
